  "prompt": "What is the location and function of a lysosome?",
  "response": "Here's a detailed overview of lysosomes:\n\nLocation:\n- Found in the cytoplasm of eukaryotic cells\n- Typically located near the cell nucleus\n- Present in most animal cells and some plant cells\n- More abundant in cells with high metabolic activity\n\nFunction:\n1. Cellular digestion\n- Break down various cellular materials like proteins, lipids, carbohydrates, and nucleic acids\n- Contain hydrolytic enzymes that can digest complex molecules into simpler compounds\n\n2. Waste disposal\n- Eliminate old or damaged cellular organelles\n- Break down and recycle cellular debris\n- Remove unnecessary or non-functional cellular components\n\n3. Intracellular defense\n- Destroy foreign particles and pathogens\n- Participate in immune response by breaking down invading microorganisms\n\n4. Autophagy\n- Help in recycling cellular materials during starvation\n- Digest and reuse cellular components to generate energy\n\n5. Programmed cell death (apoptosis)\n- Release enzymes that contribute to cell death processes\n\nStructural characteristics:\n- Membrane-bound organelle\n- Spherical or oval-shaped\n- Contain acidic internal environment (pH around 4.5-5)\n- Equipped with powerful digestive enzymes",
